Offset !! size !! Description |- | 0x0000000 || 0x7000000 || Wholeflash |- | 0x0000000 || 0x0040000 || Bootloader |- | 0x0040000 || 0x0020000 || wifi |- | 0x0060000 || 0x0040000 || tag |- | 0x00a0000 || 0x0160000 || config |- | 0x0200000 || 0x0400000 || kernel1 |- | 0x0600000 || 0x1400000 || rootfs1 |- | 0x1a00000 || 0x0400000 || kernel2 |- | 0x1e00000 || 0x1400000 || rootfs2 |} Flash backup: [https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&id=1mtQ4jSYT5YLQxWVEtlk5nxtpmjHTcnIh h367n-flash-backup.tar.gz] ===Bootloader Recovery mode=== We can enter into the bootloader recovery mode: # Set a static IP on your computer, use 192.168.1.35 (or any compatible), and connect the ethernet cable to the router. # Power off the device (unplug the PSU) # Puss down '''Reset''' and '''WPS''' button at the same time # Power on the device # Wait 5 seconds # Release the buttons # Browse to http://192.168.1.254, you should see this screen: [[File:H367A-bootloader-web.png]] ===Bootloader=== We can break into the Bootloader command line by pressing :the key 1 while starting up the device. There are some commands available for unbricking the device:

==Command injection== There is a possibility to inject commands via web interface using the ''URL Filter'' field at Internet->Security section [[File:H367a-com injection.png|500px|thumb|none]] Note that here we use a custom script located at the ''var'' directory because apparently the scripts at the usb flash drives under the ''/mnt'' directory can't be executed. We can write files to ''/var'' using a popular samba server bug. ===Boot log=== {{SCollapse|boot log |
